---
import TutorialLayout from '../../../layouts/TutorialLayout.astro';
import TutorialPlayground from '../../../components/TutorialPlayground.astro';
---

<TutorialLayout 
  title="Hello, World!" 
  description="Your first Python program"
  currentPage={2}
  totalPages={10}
  prevLink="/en/materi/01-intro"
  nextLink="/en/materi/03-variables"
>
  <!-- Preload Pyodide for better performance -->
  <script>
    // Preload Pyodide when user shows intent to use playground
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      // Preload on hover or focus of playground area
      const playground = document.querySelector('[data-playground]');
      if (playground) {
        const preload = () => {
          import('/src/lib/pyodide-runtime.js').then(({ preloadPyodide }) => {
            preloadPyodide();
          });
        };
        
        playground.addEventListener('mouseenter', preload, { once: true });
        playground.addEventListener('focusin', preload, { once: true });
      }
    });
  </script>

  <div slot="content">
    <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
    
    <p>Welcome to your first Python lesson! Let's start with the traditional "Hello, World!" program.</p>
    
    <h2>The print() function</h2>
    
    <p>In Python, we use the <code>print()</code> function to display text on the screen. Here's how it works:</p>
    
    <ul>
      <li><code>print()</code> is a built-in function in Python</li>
      <li>You put the text you want to display inside parentheses</li>
      <li>Text (strings) must be enclosed in quotes</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>Types of Quotes</h2>
    
    <p>Python accepts various types of quotes:</p>
    
    <ul>
      <li><code>"Hello, World!"</code> - Double quotes</li>
      <li><code>'Hello, World!'</code> - Single quotes</li>
      <li><code>"""Hello, World!"""</code> - Triple quotes for long text</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>Try it yourself</h2>
    
    <p>Look at the code on the right. Click the "Run" button to execute it and see the output.</p>
    
    <p>Try modifying the text inside the quotes and run it again!</p>
    
    <h2>What you learned</h2>
    
    <ul>
      <li>How to use the <code>print()</code> function</li>
      <li>How to display text in Python</li>
      <li>The importance of quotes around text</li>
      <li>Different types of quotes you can use</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>Ready for the next lesson? Click "Next" to learn about variables!</p>
  </div>

  <div slot="playground" data-playground>
    <TutorialPlayground 
      code={`print("Hello, World!")
print("Welcome to Python programming!")

# Try changing the text above and click Run!
# You can also add more print statements:
print("This is my first Python program")

# Try different types of quotes:
print('Using single quotes')
print("Using double quotes")

# Display multiple lines at once
print("""This is text
that consists of
multiple lines""")`}
    />
  </div>
</TutorialLayout>